< Text>
I have heard of New Autos Inc a few times around town and had seen their license plates, but never gave them much thought until my parents had bought a truck from Ken and absolutely loved the experience. Within a few weeks of my parents purchasing, my fiance and I were in the market for a new Subaru Outback and had been doing some online shopping and pricing it out. But like some people, I was avoiding going into the dealership because I really don't enjoy the a salesman all over your every move, and having to run in the back room every time you make a offer on a vehicle to check with "the man". My Dad told me to give Ken a call. I called Ken and instantly his knowledge of vehicles shined through, he rattled off all of the questions about the Outback to pin point exactly what we were looking for over the phone in under a minute and I instantly had the feeling that this guy knew vehicles. I went into his office to meet him about an hour later and in that time he had the exactly model picked out we were talking of and all we had to talk about was the price. After all of my research online, Ken had the vehicle come in below what I was expecting to pay against the invoice price and below my monthly payment price, and all we had to do was pick out a color and wait for delivery. He even was able to show me what the "average price paid" range in our area and where we were going to fall into that spectrum, and yes, it was the very bottom end. It was really that easy. We put the money down and Ken said our new car was on a truck bound for California and to expect it within a week. A week later, we came in, signed the paperwork and drove home happy. I recommend New Autos Inc to anybody in the market for a new vehicle, it is a true no hassle buying experience!</Text>

<user_name>Sydney Song<//user_name><Time>1582346693521< /Time>< Rating>
4</Rating>
< Review>
AYCE Korean BBQ at fair price. Granted that the quality of the meats is ok and the selection is limited to only 6, like spencer steak, pork belly, spicy pork, chadol beef, marinated chicken and bulgogi. The banchans are vary and prepared surprisingly well. The dining room is what you expect from a no-frills family restaurant. The service is brisk and efficient, the busy servers don't have the time to chitchat. Above average compared to other Korean BBQ places in the SF vicinity. Also the final tab will also automatically include the 15% gratuity- I was going to tip more but hey, 15% is what they're going to get if they are going to include it in your bill.</Review>

0x808f79883aefecb5:0x90af3e40e4053b2a<//GmapID>
<pics>None<//pics>< Text>
Pricey.. but man.. what a meal (the BBQ at your table feast).  The meats were pre-seasoned.. but you cook them at the table with various add on seasonsings like soy bean paste (yum! never had that before), raw garlic, kimchees, etc.  What an incredible set of flavors. I've had a bit of korean BBQ.. even made my own at home. but I was so glad t otry these guys out and see how it's really done. Was a bit expensive.. and I would have appreciated a bit of coaching on what flavors go with what. espcecially for folks who have never had Korean and get a table full of raw + picked ingredients, and a pair of sissors.. hehe.. they muc hreally be confused. But I was a happy camper there tonight. Just dom't "over kimchee" as I often do, or your spouse/friends may complain for the next couple of days.. ;)< /Text>

1412722630508</Date>
< user_name>
Sherry Li< /user_name>
< Review>
So happy I found another great Korean place near my new place. Korean BBQ House is a full-on Korean restaurant complete with grill at your table BBQs, all you can eat BBQ specials, and a variety of non-bbq dishes.

They seem super authentic, because there are a bunch of dishes that I've never seen before. Everybody knows that's the marker of an authentic ethnic restaurant, right?

The $20 AYCE BBQ special lets you choose between two options (see one of the photos). Sounds pretty cool.

They give you a variety of banchan - 8 when I ate there, but from other Yelpers pictures, more if you do bbq. Both the tofu soup and kimchi pancake were spot on. The tofu soup came piping hot - almost scalding my tongue, lots of beef, rich broth, and big portion of tofu.

Service was quick and courteous. Definitely worth a go!<//Review>

< text>
A hidden gem in this small townüíé

Tips:

Come early to get the nice shade spots with the beach chairs. (Ask the life guard for more chairs if you need it)

They prefer you make reservation before coming in, it‚Äôs located in the website. Random ‚ÄúWalk-ins‚Äù is not recommended due to limited capacity.

The ‚Äúfancy tent area with curtains and soft chairs‚Äù are not free, they charge $15/hr & $45/day.

The lazy water is closed down until June...

They have a concession standing for snacks and drinks plus swim diapers, life vest, etc...

There‚Äôs swimming pool for all ages and a splash pad!

Entrance fee is $8/person if you not a resident of El Centro..

The staffs are super friendly!

Overall it is a great way to spend couple hours during the hot summer months!< /text>

< Text>
This place is good. The prices for the pizza are very reasonable. $8.50 to "Publish your own" which means you can create your pizza with as many toppings you want. The pizza crust is thin and crunchy. Overall the people that work here are very friendly, the service is really great. They serve beer here as well. Topping selection is decent and include several unique items I haven't seen at similar places like rosemary. The only reason I gave it a 4 is because I like Blaze better. But definitely a place to visit and try!</Text>

<rating>4< /rating>< review>
The theme of the place is of a newspaper printing business. You walk in and ask either for a Publish Your Own Pizza or a specialty pizza. You go along the line of ingredients and they put your pizza into a rolling oven. Theres more toppings available after it's been cooked. There's a brief guessing game as to which pizza is yours and then you pay. I went during lunch hour on a Thursday and it was a bit busy; line took about 15 minutes. Other than that, good pizza. I'll definitely be coming back.<//review>

<Pics>None</Pics><Gmap_id>0x80c2bc8602a90341:0xd73874d4f138751a</Gmap_id><user_id>117338682450143437863< /user_id><Date>1621393255769</Date><response>None</response><Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
I was offered a couple of nights lodging at the UCLA Meyer and Renee Luskin Conference Center. When David, with the inside-scoop mentioned that it was 'Swank', I of course decided to give it a try. Google maps directed me into the loading dock at first, until I was able to discover the Guest Parking, located beneath the building,  accessible via a down-ramp that is adjacent to the guest drop-off / pick-up zone loop. The lobby is modern, warm, spacious with paneled details interspersed and appointed with gracious textures. The lobby has several work station areas available for guests. I was warmly greeted by the front desk staff, with comprehensive health safety protocols. The room was easily accessible from the security room-key enabled elevators. Echoing the modern motif, the room was tidy, with entry table, wardobe (with safe), integrated dresser, counter, desk & work chair, and large HDTV along the long wall, a comfortable reading chair, and king sized bed with side tables,  opposite. Numerous and well placed light fixtures facilitated getting comfortable. The bathroom is spacious with large lovely border-lit mirror and walk-in shower. The room was quite quiet :-) ...Thanks so very much for the ample hospitality and attention to detail...Thanks David, all of my 'Swank'  expectations have been exceeded!< /text>

<user>115846385659008332742<//user>< user_name>
Robin Mcelyea</user_name>
<Date>1613634690073< /Date><rate>4<//rate>< Review>
We went here yesterday for our son's eleventh birthday. The exhibits are truly amazing. The rainforest dome, the albino aligator and the penguins were my favorites, not to mention the gorgeous 'Living Roof.' The food in the cafeteria is a bit pricey, but tastes incredible. My artichoke and wheatberry salad was excellent. The entire staff is also super friendly and eager to answer any questions you may have about the exhibits. My only complaint would have to be the fact that this place is expensive as heck. After the cost of admission and a meal at the cafeteria, a family of four can easily spend over three hundred bucks. All in all though, a great experience...just expect to be charged an arm and a leg.< /Review>
